    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/rh-index-benchmark-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Relative Hemolysis Index Benchmark Comparison — FDA Pump Reference Dataset",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/hemolysis-experimental-benchmark",
      "description": "The CFD model was exercised across all five flow-speed operating points (2 L/min at 2500 RPM, 3 L/min at 3000 RPM, 4 L/min at 3500 RPM, 5 L/min at 4000 RPM, and 6 L/min at 4500 RPM) using the Giersiepen power-law hemolysis sub-model with Lagrangian particle tracking. Scalar stress histories were integrated along 5,000 representative streamlines per operating point. Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were compared against the FDA-published in-vitro experimental dataset for the generic centrifugal pump. Across all five operating points the mean absolute relative error was 8.3%, with a maximum point-wise deviation of 14.1% observed at the 2 L/min, 2500 RPM condition where recirculation zones near the volute tongue are most pronounced. The relative hemolysis index RH remained below 1.0 for all predicate comparisons, satisfying the acceptance criterion. Grid independence was confirmed on a three-level refinement study (coarse 4.2 M cells, medium 9.8 M cells, fine 21.4 M cells); the Richardson-extrapolated discretization uncertainty for NIH was 3.1% at the fine level. Turbulence closure used the SST k-omega model; sensitivity runs with the realizable k-epsilon model showed less than 2% variation in NIH. Blood rheology was modeled as a Newtonian fluid with dynamic viscosity 0.0035 Pa·s and density 1060 kg/m³, consistent with the experimental conditions reported in the benchmark dataset. All boundary conditions were matched to the experimental test rig: inlet velocity profiles derived from Doppler ultrasound measurements, outlet static pressure set to 60 mmHg gauge. The simulation campaign was executed on the university HPC cluster (48-core nodes, InfiniBand fabric) using OpenFOAM v9 with double-precision arithmetic. Convergence was declared when all residuals fell below 1×10⁻⁶ and NIH varied by less than 0.05% over the final 500 iterations. This comprehensive validation exercise provides strong evidence that the CFD model captures the dominant hemolysis mechanisms at MRL 2 fidelity."
    },
